    }
</style>



<!--Admin-->

@if (User.IsInRole("Admin"))
{
    <ul class="navbar-nav">
        <li class="nav-item">
            <a type="submit" style=" color:black" asp-area="Identity" asp-page="/Account/Logout">Logout</a>
        </li>
    </ul>

    <div>
        <h1>Administrator User Manual</h1>

        <h2>Landing Page</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Forms that require your attention are listed at the top and are highlighted garnet. These forms are also marked "Pending DER Approval"</li>
            <li>To visit a form that requires your attention and fill our your portion, click View</li>
            <li>Forms that do not require your attention are listed underneath the thin double lines</li>
            <li>You may view any form at any time, though you will not be able to fill out any fields when you click View on forms that do not require your attentions</li>
            <li>Once you click submit and the status code is 3, an email will be sent to you for confirmation, the student, and Student Services</li>
            <li>Once you click submit and the status code is 5, an email will be sent to you for confirmation, the student, and the Faculty of Record</li>
            <li>Once you click submit and the status code is 7, an email will be sent to you for confirmation and to the student</li>
        </ul>
        <h2>Display Form</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Once you click View on a form, you will be directed to the Display Form page for that particular form</li>
            <li>If this form does require your attention, there will be some fields for you to fill out that are not grayed out</li>
            <li>If this form does not require your attention, you will still be able to view all data currently in the form, you just cannot edit it</li>
        </ul>
        <h2>Templates Overview Page</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>This page shows all active, in-progress, and retired templates</li>
            <li>You can only have one active template at a time</li>
            <li>If you want to make a new template Active, you must first retire the current Active template</li>
            <li>If you wish to retire an active template, there cannot be any students currently using it</li>
            <li>The current active template may be retired if all forms referencing it are either Accepted, Declined, or Withdrawn</li>
            <li>In-Progress templates are the ones you are currently editing or creating</li>
            <li>Retired templates are those that are currently not being edited, created, or used by any students</li>
            <li>You can make a Retired template to In-Progress status for you to edit and then move to Active </li>
        </ul>
        <br />
    </div>

}

